\begin_layout Section
Euclidean hyperspherical embedding of networks
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this work we consider undirected connected simple graphs 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma=\left(V,E\right)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is the set of vertices or nodes and 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

is the set of edges. Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A=A\left(\Gamma\right)=\left[A_{ij}\right]_{n\times n}$
\end_inset

 be the adjacency matrix of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

. Because the graphs considered here are undirected the associated adjacency matrix is symmetric, and its eigenvalues are real. We label the eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 in non-increasing order: 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1}>\lambda_{2}\geq\ldots\geq\lambda_{n}$
\end_inset

. Since 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a real-valued, symmetric matrix, we can decompose 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $A=U\Lambda U^{T}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 is a diagonal matrix containing the eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U=[\mathbf{\overrightarrow{\psi}}_{1},\ldots,\mathbf{\overrightarrow{\psi}}_{n}]$
\end_inset

 is orthogonal, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\overrightarrow{\psi}}_{i}$
\end_inset

 is an eigenvector associated with 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}$
\end_inset

. We denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\mathbf{\psi}}_{j,u}$
\end_inset

 the 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

th entry of the 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 th eigenvector of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

. A row of the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 corresponding to the node 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 of the graph is designated here by the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\varphi}_{i}=\left[\mathbf{\mathbf{\psi}}_{1,i},\ldots\mathbf{\mathbf{\psi}}_{n,i}\right]^{T}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An important quantity for studying communication processes in networks is the so-called communicability function 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after ""
before ""
key "Communicability,Estrada_Higham,Estrada_Hatano_Benzi"

\end_inset

, which is defined as follows. 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 be two nodes of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

, then the communicability function between these two nodes is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition

\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
G_{uv}=\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\frac{\left(A^{k}\right)_{uv}}{k!}=\left(\exp\left(A\right)\right)_{uv}=\sum_{k=1}^{n}e^{\lambda_{k}}\mathbf{\mathbf{\psi}}_{k,u}\mathbf{\psi}_{k,v}.
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It counts the total number of walks starting at node 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 and ending at node 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

, weighted in decreasing order of their length by a factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{k!}$
\end_inset

. That is, the communicability function considers shorter walks more influential than longer ones and penalize them appropriately such that the whole series converges. The 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{uu}$
\end_inset

 terms of the communicability function characterize the degree of participation of a node in all subgraphs of the network, giving more weight to the smaller ones. Thus, it is known as the subgraph centrality of the corresponding node 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after ""
before ""
key "Subgraph_Centrality"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now define a parameter that account for the difference between the number of weighted closed walks that start at (and return to) the corresponding nodes 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

, and the number of weighted walks that start at node 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 (respectively 
\begin_inset Formula $v)$
\end_inset

 and ends at the node 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 (respectively 
\begin_inset Formula $u).$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 be two nodes of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

, then 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\xi_{uv}^{2}=G_{uu}+G_{vv}-2G_{uv}
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This difference, which is defined below as 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{uv}^{2}$
\end_inset

 serves as a quantification of the potential quality of communication channels between two nodes. That is, if there are many routes that connect nodes 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 together, and there are not many routes that starting at the node 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 (respectively 
\begin_inset Formula $v)$
\end_inset

 return to it, we can say that most of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

information
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 departing the node 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 (respectively 
\begin_inset Formula $v)$
\end_inset

 with destination to the node 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 (respectively 
\begin_inset Formula $u)$
\end_inset

 will arrive at it. Thus, there is a potential good quality of communication between these two nodes. The other way around is very clear as if there are many returning routes to the nodes and very few connecting them, most of the information departing one node will hardly arrive at the other. In a similar way we can define the ratio between the communicability between the two nodes and the product of the self-communicabilities of both nodes. 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 be two nodes of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

, then 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\gamma_{uv}=\dfrac{G_{uv}}{\sqrt{G_{uu}G_{vv}}}.\label{eq:comm_angle}
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then, we have proved the following result. 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 be two nodes of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{uv}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{uv}$
\end_inset

 the parameters defined before. Then, 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{uv}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is a square Euclidean distance between the two nodes and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{uv}=\cos^{-1}\gamma_{uv}$
\end_inset

 is the Euclidean angle spanned between the positions vectors of the two nodes in a Euclidean space. 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Althought we are not proving the result here we sketch the procedure of its proof. The matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $G=\exp\left(A\right)$
\end_inset

 is positive define, and so we can express it as a Gram matrix of the form
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
G=X^{T}X,
\end{equation}
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\left[\vec{x}_{1},\ldots,\vec{x}_{n}\right]$
\end_inset

 and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\vec{x}_{u}=\exp\left(\varLambda/2\right)\vec{\varphi}_{u},
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then, it is straightforward to realize that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\begin{array}{lll}
\vec{x}_{u}\cdot\vec{x}_{u} & =\left(\exp\left(\varLambda/2\right)\vec{\varphi}_{u}\right)^{T}\exp\left(\varLambda/2\right)\vec{\varphi}_{v}\\
 & =\vec{\varphi}_{u}^{T}\exp\left(\varLambda/2\right)\exp\left(\varLambda/2\right)\vec{\varphi}_{v}\\
 & =\vec{\varphi}_{u}^{T}\exp\left(\varLambda\right)\vec{\varphi}_{v}\\
 & =\sum_{k=1}^{n}e^{\lambda_{k}}\mathbf{\mathbf{\psi}}_{k,u}\mathbf{\psi}_{k,v}\\
 & =G_{uv.}
\end{array}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

Then, we can express 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{uv}^{2}$
\end_inset

 in terms of the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}_{u}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}_{v}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\begin{array}{ll}
\xi_{uv}^{2} & =\vec{x}_{u}\cdot\vec{x}_{u}+\vec{x}_{v}\cdot\vec{x}_{v}-2\vec{x}_{u}\cdot\vec{x}_{v}\\
 & =\left\Vert \vec{x}_{u}-\vec{x}_{v}\right\Vert ^{2},
\end{array}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

which means that 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{uv}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is a Euclidean distance (metric) between the corresponding nodes and that 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}_{u}$
\end_inset

 is the position vector of the corresponding node in such Euclidean space. It is now obvious that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\cos\theta_{uv}=\dfrac{\vec{x}_{u}\cdot\vec{x}_{v}}{\left\Vert \vec{x}_{u}\right\Vert \left\Vert \vec{x}_{v}\right\Vert }=\dfrac{G_{uv}}{\sqrt{G_{uu}G_{vv}}}=\gamma_{uv}.
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is important to remark here that the embedding induced by the communicability function is in a Euclidean hypersphere as proved in the following result. 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 be a simple connected graph. Then, 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}_{u}$
\end_inset

 is a vector pointing from the origin of an 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(n-1\right)$
\end_inset

-sphere to its surface where the node 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is located. The radius of this hypersphere is given by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after ""
before ""
key "Angles"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem

\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
R^{2}=\frac{1}{4}\left(c-\frac{\left(2-b\right)^{2}}{a}\right),
\end{equation}
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a=\vec{1}^{T}\exp\left(-A\right)\vec{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $b=\vec{s}^{T}\exp\left(-A\right)\vec{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $c=\vec{s}^{T}\exp\left(-A\right)\vec{s}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{s}={\rm diag}(\exp\left(A\right))$
\end_inset

. 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This means that the communicability function induces an embedding of every connected simple graph of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 nodes into the surface of a Euclidean 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(n-1\right)$
\end_inset

-sphere. The case of two graphs with 3 nodes is illustrated in Fig. XX.
\end_layout

